ThinkPart(
    type='think',
    think='Now I have a good understanding of the PR. Let me compile my findings
:\n\n**Architecture Review:**\n1. The PR introduces `internal/pkg/eventbus` as a
shared package for the unified event bus.\n2. The architecture follows the patte
rn: Data layer creates `StreamPublisher`/`StreamConsumer`/`EventBus`, Biz layer 
injects `StreamPublisher` and publishes events, Server layer wraps consumer as k
ratos Server.\n3. There\'s a pre-existing architecture issue in `MarketService` 
where the Service layer directly calls `repo.MarketRepo`, `repo.UserFishRepo`, e
tc. instead of going through the Biz layer only. But this is pre-existing and no
t introduced by this PR.\n4. The DI wiring looks correct in wire.go and wire_gen
.go.\n\n**Code Style:**\n1. gofmt is clean.\n2. Naming follows Go conventions.\n
3. Error handling is generally good - events are published after transaction com
mit, and publish failures are logged but don\'t fail the main operation.\n4. One
issue: `MarkProcessed` in `idempotent.go` uses `Set` without `NX` flag, contrary
to the design doc which specifies `SET ... NX EX`. This means it could overwrite
an existing key and extend TTL unexpectedly.\n\n**Test Coverage:**\n1. `internal
/pkg/eventbus` has 79.3% coverage - this meets the >= 70% requirement for the ne
w code.\n2. The overall `internal/biz/wapi` tests fail, but those are pre-existi
ng failures in `user_test.go`, not related to this PR.\n3. There are no tests fo
r the changed biz files (`mixing.go`, `market.go`, `building_map.go`), but the p
roject overall has very low biz layer test coverage.\n\n**Performance & Security
:**\n1. In `event_dispatch_server.go`, `go e.publishEvent(ctx, event)` launches 
an unbounded goroutine per event. This is a potential goroutine leak/performance
issue under high load.\n2. In `bus.go`, `Publish` uses `gopool` which is bounded
(1024), so that\'s safer.\n3. The `streamKey` function in `publisher.go` uses `i
nt(userID) % p.partition` which could overflow on 32-bit, but this is a minor co
ncern.\n4. No SQL injection risks - all events use protobuf.\n\n**Key Issues Fou
nd:**\n1. **High/Medium**: `event_dispatch_server.go` launches unbounded gorouti
ne per event (`go e.publishEvent(ctx, event)`). Should use a bounded pool like i
n `bus.go`.\n2. **Medium**: `idempotent.go` `MarkProcessed` doesn\'t use `NX` fl
ag. The design doc says to use `SET ... NX EX` but it uses `Set(ctx, key, "1", c
.ttl)` which doesn\'t ensure the key was only set if not exist. This breaks the 
idempotency contract if called concurrently.\n3. **Low**: The PR claims 83.9% te
st coverage in the PR description, but the actual `eventbus` package coverage is
79.3%. This is still above 70% though.\n\nLet me check if there are any other is
sues. In `consumer.go`:\n- `ensureConsumerGroup` checks for `"BUSYGROUP Consumer
Group name already exists"` string error. This is fragile but common with Redis.
\n- `retryOrDLQ` ACKs the message before retrying/DLQ, which means if the retry 
fails to write, the message is lost. But this is acceptable for event bus semant
ics.\n\nWait, let me re-read the idempotent issue. The `IsProcessed` function re
turns `val == "1"`. If `MarkProcessed` is called twice for the same event (e.g.,
concurrent consumers), the second call will still succeed and extend the TTL. Th
is doesn\'t break idempotency per se because `IsProcessed` will still return tru
e, but the TTL extension could be undesirable. However, more importantly, there\
's a race condition window between `IsProcessed` and `MarkProcessed` where two c
onsumers could both pass the check and then both process the event. Using `SET N
X EX` would close this race window because the check and mark would be atomic.\n
\nActually, looking more carefully at the consumer flow:\n1. `IsProcessed` is ca
lled\n2. If false, `processor.Process` is called\n3. Then `MarkProcessed` is cal
led\n\nBetween step 1 and 3, another consumer could also process the same event.
The design doc explicitly mentions `SET nx:event:handled:{event_id} 1 NX EX 8640
0` but the implementation doesn\'t use `NX`. This is a real gap.\n\nFor the `eve
nt_dispatch_server.go` goroutine issue, this is a blocking concern for high thro
ughput.\n\nLet me now write the review report.',
    encrypted=None
)
