gopool which is bounded.\n2. In `internal/server/wapi/event_consumer_server.go`,
`Start` launches a goroutine but returns immediately without checking if the con
sumer actually started. This is standard for kratos servers though.\n3. In `inte
rnal/server/wcore/wcc/event_dispatch_server.go`, line 93: `go e.publishEvent(ctx
, event)` - this launches a goroutine for every event without any bounds check. 
This could be a performance issue under high load.\n4. The `streamKey` function 
in `publisher.go` uses `int(userID) % p.partition` - this could overflow for lar
ge userIDs on 32-bit systems, but it\'s fine on 64-bit.\n5. `MarkProcessed` in `
idempotent.go` uses `Set` without `NX` flag, which means it could overwrite an e
xisting key. The design doc mentions using `SET nx:event:handled:{event_id} 1 NX
EX 86400` but the actual implementation doesn\'t use `NX` or `EX` together - it 
uses `Set(ctx, key, "1", c.ttl)` which does set the TTL but doesn\'t use NX. Thi
s is a potential issue.\n\nLet me read eventbus.go and check the idempotent impl
ementation more carefully.',
